A Beanstalk project has one config file, one source root, and generated output folders.

### Where things live

- `config.bst` at the project root controls build settings.
- `src/` (or whatever `entry_root` says) holds your source files.
- `lib/` holds project-local source-backed packages by default. Each direct child becomes a package prefix.
- `dev/` and `release/` are generated output. Do not edit them.

### One root file per module directory

Each source directory can have one `#*.bst` file that marks it as a module. The `#` filename is just a convention. `#page.bst`, `#api.bst` and `#mod.bst` all mean the same thing to the compiler.

### Outputs are generated

The build command creates output folders. They are not source. The builder cleans up stale artifacts automatically.

### Remember

- `config.bst` is the only config file.
- `#*.bst` files are module roots.
- `dev/` and `release/` are generated.
